{{Infobox organization | name = Max Planck Institute for Mathematics | image = Bonn Altstadt Max-Planck-Institut.jpg | size = | alt = | caption = | map = | map_size = | map_alt = | map_caption = | abbreviation = MPIM | motto = | predecessor = | successor = | formation = {{Start date and age|1980}} | extinction = | type = Scientific institute | status = | purpose = Research in [[mathematics]] | headquarters = [[Bonn]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]], [[Germany]] | location = | coords = | region_served = | membership = | language = | general = | leader_title = | leader_name = | key_people = [[Friedrich Hirzebruch]], founder. [[Gerd Faltings]], [[Peter Scholze]] fields medalists. | main_organ = | parent_organization = [[Max Planck Society]] | affiliations = | num_staff = | num_volunteers = | budget = | website = [http://www.mpim-bonn.mpg.de/ {{en icon}}] | remarks = | former name = }}
The '''Max Planck Institute for Mathematics''' ({{lang-de|Max-Planck-Institut für Mathematik}}, '''MPIM''') is a prestigious research institute located in [[Bonn]], [[Germany]]. It is named in honor of the [[Germany|German]] [[physicist]] [[Max Planck]] and forms part of the [[Max Planck Society]] (''Max-Planck-Gesellschaft''), an association of 84 institutes engaging in fundamental research in the arts and the sciences. The MPIM is the only Max Planck institute specializing in [[pure mathematics]].
The Institute was founded by [[Friedrich Hirzebruch]] in 1980, having emerged from the collaborative research center "Theoretical Mathematics" ([[:de:Sonderforschungsbereich|Sonderforschungsbereich]] "Theoretische Mathematik"). Hirzebruch shaped the institute as its director until his retirement in 1995. Currently, the institute is managed by a board of five directors consisting of [[Peter Teichner]] (managing director), [[Werner Ballmann]], [[Gerd Faltings]], [[Peter Scholze]], and [[Don Zagier]]. [[Friedrich Hirzebruch]] was, and [[Yuri Manin]] and [[Günter Harder]] are, acting as [[emeriti]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mpim-bonn.mpg.de/node/91 |author=Max Planck Institute for Mathematics |accessdate=April 25, 2014 |title=About the MPIM}}</ref>
==Research== The Max Planck Institute for Mathematics offers mathematicians from around the world the opportunity to visit Bonn and engage in [[sabbatical]] work lasting from weeks to several months. This guest program distinguishes the MPIM from other Max Planck institutes, and results in only a limit number of permanent positions <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mpim-bonn.mpg.de/node/91 |author=Max Planck Institute for Mathematics |accessdate=April 25, 2014 |title=About the MPIM}}</ref> and the absence of separate departments within the institute.
The research of the members and guests of the institute can be classified into the following areas:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mpim-bonn.mpg.de/node/76 |author=Max Planck Institute for Mathematics |accessdate=April 25, 2014 |title=Guest program}}</ref>
* [[Algebraic geometry|Algebraic Geometry]] and [[Complex geometry|Complex Geometry]] * [[Algebraic group|Algebraic Groups]] * [[Algebraic Topology]] * [[Arithmetic Geometry]] * [[Differential Geometry]] and [[differential topology|Topology]] * [[Dynamical Systems]] * [[Global analysis|Global Analysis]] * [[Mathematical Physics]] * [[Noncommutative geometry|Noncommutative Geometry]] * [[Number Theory]] * [[Representation Theory]]
